{"key":"processedPost-15668885","value":{"id":15668885,"first":15668643,"last":15668885,"when":1326646308,"utime":"01/15/12 06:51 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Jw6457 said:</b><br />What's a typical time to let wbs dry after simmering and rinsing in colonder one last time. Worried about having the moisture content correct.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />You're letting the tail wag the dog.&nbsp; You want the grains totally dry on the outside.&nbsp; The moisture you want is on the inside.<br /><br />Never rinse after boiling, because this cools off the grains.&nbsp; Rinse the dry grains before you boil, and then when you pour it into the colander, the water will drain, and the surface moisture will steam off.&nbsp; By shaking the colander a few times, you can get more steam to rise off the grains, leaving them dry.<br /><br />The procedure is demonstrated in full on the \"Let's Grow Mushrooms\" DVD, a <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-Preparation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">sample clip</a> of which can be viewed on my site.<br />RR","title":"Re: How long should I let wbs dry after simmering and rinsing?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}